Intuition
Every backtracking problem is:
STATE → CHOICES → RECURSE → UNDO

We need to generate all possible arrangements of the given numbers.

At each step, instead of moving in a fixed order, we decide:

“Which number should I place next in my permutation?”

Since every number can appear exactly once, at every position we choose from the set of unused elements.

So the problem becomes:

Build a permutation step-by-step by picking any unused element at each level.

This naturally forms a decision tree where:

Each level represents one position in the permutation
Each branch represents choosing one available number

We continue until the permutation has length n.

Complexity
Time complexity:
O(n*n!) There are n! permutations
Each takes O(n) to copy into result

Space complexity:
O(n) recursion depth + used array (excluding output)

Code
class Solution:
    def permute(self, nums: List[int]) -> List[List[int]]:
        diary , result , n = [] , [] , len(nums)
        used = [False] * n
        def backtrack():
            if len(diary) == len(nums):
                result.append(diary.copy())
                return
            for i in range(len(nums)):
                if used[i] == False:
                    diary.append(nums[i])
                    used[i] = True
                    backtrack()
                    diary.pop()
                    used[i] = False
        backtrack()
        return result
